</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ bxQNyP pf-27_">Slow heart rate and decreased sweating
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ bxQNyP pf-29_">Irregular periods, anemia, constipation</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ bxQNyP pf-31_">Memory issues, etc.</li></ul><p class="sc-gIDmLj eMdhGW pf-33_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3" data-animation="fadeIn">The symptoms would usually appear gradually, with the continuously decreasing thyroid function.</p><h2 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" data-animation="fadeIn" class="sc-brSvTw kXcmVH pf-35_">How do you treat hypothyroidism?
</h2><p class="sc-gIDmLj eMdhGW pf-37_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3" data-animation="fadeIn">Hypothyroidism can be safely and effectively treated today, usually with the use of supplementation. Changes in lifestyle — for example, cutting down sugar and starting to lead a more active life — are usually recommended by the specialists along with the medications.<br><br>If hypothyroidism occurs due to iodine or some other trace mineral deficiency, it can be replenished with supplements.

